</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/ugeny.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Geny</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#330000>(1/23/02 12:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.escaflowneonline.com/images/folken10.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question on crowd control</span><hr size=1> The most annoying aspect of multiple adds is the fact that the mobs will run on top of each other.  In other words it may look like just one mob, but really there's like 2 or 3 of them stacked on top of each other.  In that situation, have the tank engage and everyone else assist.  Then you just keep clicking on the mobs that have full or nearly full health and mez.  If you're working with a good tank, then they would take a step back to separate the mobs so it'll be easier for you to handle.  Also, by waiting for the tank to engage, the other mobs might jump onto someone else making it easier for you to figure out which one to mez.<br>
<br>
Trias Epione<br>
60th Mental Patient <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/ukerosion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>kErosion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#330000>(1/24/02 5:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question on crowd control</span><hr size=1> I add (PLEASE STEP BACK!) to the end of my mez messages just because of that stacking situation on multi-pulls.  When I'm hunting with melee that have hunted with me a while that's usually all it takes to get them to take a step back and make it much easier on me to pick out the next mez in the pack, as well as making it very much easier on me to re-mez when monsters are getting near the breaking point.<br>
<br>
In most xp groups I can wing it without the melee members doing this, but when heading into areas with a risk of massive overpulls I'll take a second to break down the importance of stepping back after a mez and why it makes getting and KEEPING everything mezzed quicker.<br>
<br>
Nothing drives me nuts like a multi-puller who refuses to learn this rule and can't figure out how chain-pulling works. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uladihawk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ladihawk</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#330000>(1/25/02 2:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question on crowd control</span><hr size=1> My number 1 peeve is when i have mesed all in sight and with my mes message it says to &quot;assist the tank/puller only&quot; then see someone attack that nice red gnoll i had finally got to sleep. Both of the replies here are very good suggestions and i will put both into action soon. Thank you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><br><p align="left"><img
