</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uzallarenya.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zallarenya</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#330000>(2/9/02 9:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.outburst.com/ray/Zsteins.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question on crowd control</span><hr size=1> These are very good replies in this thread. I would like to add my comment.<br>
<br>
One person said that all attackers must /assist the main tank, and the main tank will make the calls as to which mobs to fight next.<br>
<br>
In most cases, this is fine, but I've found in areas with a large number of mobs and adds, the crowd controller (the enchanter) is best suited to make the call at what's next. I've had some tanks ask me to make the calls, even. Many main tanks are very aware of the order of adds and mezzes and strength of mobs, but they have a lot of other tasks to deal with. The crowd controller knows the state of the mobs better than anyone. The enchanter knows which mobs are going to be difficult to control (resisting mez repeatedly for example) and should be killed first.<br>
<br>
In fights where you have to keep several mobs mezzed for a long time, you'll run low on mana. Having to apply more mezzes than necessary will run you out of mana quick, and spell death for the group. Have the tank kill a problem mob next, or even switch targets if necessary (only recommended for VERY good groups). Tell the tank to kill the mob that's been mezzed longest which you know will be breaking any second now, rather than the tank picking the one you happen to have just mezzed and wasting the mana you used.<br>
<br>
In most groups, though, the enchanters role is more simple. The tank chooses what to fight, the enchanter takes care of the rest.<br>
<br>
Zall <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uinnovatorius.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Innovatorius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#330000>(2/12/02 6:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home1.stofanet.dk/skottun/Innovatorius/images/00tcal_12.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question on crowd control</span><hr size=1> One thing to add to all the good comments here. As the enchanter of a decent but inexperienced group of people - that is...inexperienced in working well with a chanter in the ways described above - don't be afraid to tell people &quot;try to do this or that since it will make crowd control easier and you die less&quot;....the enchanter is the traffic cop...and if the SWAT captain aka Main Tank doesn't know how to lead...then make sure that you tell people what you want them to do.<br>
<br>
It will educate people in use of the above tactics...and you may be known as a &quot;bossy&quot; chanter....but believe me....people like bossy chanters better than groups being wiped out.<br>
<br>
A few more tips:<br>
<br>
Learn the radius of your AE mez....it can save you if the *BEEP* hits the fan. Trouble with it is that single mez cannot overwrite AE mez and vice versa....if you AE mez due to the necessity - and you are working with an experienced MT - you may ask the MT to hit a mez'ed mob once...single mez it....next AE mez'ed mob hit, single mez it...that way, you get the mez'es spread out....OR you can just keep the AE mez going....but the AE mez doesn't last as long as single (well..not any more at lvl 52) so another option is to make sure you're cleric is doing his job and keeping an eye on your health...and then just take a few hits while you single mez the group of mobs individually (that is my preferred).<br>
<br>
Use yourself as timer for buffs...you can do that by casting on yourself first, then on those who need it....as our buffs are fixed time buffs, then when yours start blinking, the others' buffs will be starting to blink soon too - the only one that is too slow and too mana expensive to cast like this is really the haste buff<br>
<br>
